      <header class="cod-title-block">
        <p class="cod-chapter-label">Chapter Five · Christian or Demonic?</p>
        <h1 class="cod-title">Language &amp; Symbols</h1>
        <p class="cod-subtitle">Do You Know What You're Worshipping?</p>
        <p class="cod-tagline">The cross belonged to Tammuz. The fish belonged to Dagon. Ezekiel already called the sunrise service the greatest abomination.</p>
      </header>

      <p class="cod-pullquote">The symbols did not switch sides. They switched labels.</p>

      <section class="cod-part"><p class="cod-part-label">Introduction</p><h2 class="cod-part-title">The Question No One Is Asking</h2><div class="cod-part-rule"></div></section>
      <p class="cod-body">Walk into almost any Christian building in the world and you will see the same set of objects. A cross mounted on the wall. A fish sticker on the door. Candles burning at the altar. A circle of light — a halo — painted above the heads of the saints in the stained glass. An Easter sunrise service on the calendar. A steeple reaching into the sky outside. Most believers have seen these things so often, from so young, that they have stopped seeing them at all.</p>
      <p class="cod-body">Ask the average churchgoer where the cross came from, and he will say it came from Calvary. Ask him where the fish came from, and he will quote you something about fishers of men. Ask him about the halo, the candles, the steeple, the sunrise service — and he will assume all of it was handed down from the apostles. <strong>Almost none of it was.</strong></p>
      <p class="cod-body">Every object in that list has a history older than Christianity. Most of them were already in use, as sacred objects, in the religions Scripture condemns. The apostles did not invent these symbols. They did not bring them out of Jerusalem. The symbols were waiting in the Greco-Roman world when Christianity entered it, and they were grafted onto the new religion as Rome absorbed it. By the time the finished product reached the English-speaking world, the origins had been forgotten and the objects had been re-labeled.</p>
      <p class="cod-body">This chapter is going to walk through the most common ones. Not to shame anyone who has unknowingly lived with them. To wake them up. The symbols did not switch sides when Christianity took them over. <strong>They switched labels.</strong> The question is whether a believer who claims to worship Yahuah in spirit and in truth can keep worshipping Him inside the language and the symbols of the system that hated Him.</p>

      <section class="cod-part"><p class="cod-part-label">Part One</p><h2 class="cod-part-title">The Cross</h2><div class="cod-part-rule"></div></section>

      <div class="cod-symbol-intro">
        <div class="cod-symbol-glyph">✝</div>
        <p class="cod-symbol-name">the most widespread and the most misunderstood</p>
      </div>

      <p class="cod-body">Start with the biggest one. The cross hangs in every sanctuary, around most Christian necks, over most Christian graves. It is assumed, without examination, to be the universal symbol of the death of the Messiah. <strong>It is not.</strong></p>
      <p class="cod-body">The Greek word the New Testament uses for the object Yahushua died on is <em>stauros</em>. Every New Testament scholar knows that <em>stauros</em>, in the first-century Greek in which the apostles wrote, meant an upright pole or stake. Not two pieces of wood intersecting. A single vertical beam. The Latin word that translated it — <em>crux</em> — could refer to several shapes: a simple stake, a T-shape, a + shape, or an X. Execution in the Roman world was performed on whatever wood was at hand, most commonly a single standing post. The two-beamed, four-pointed Latin cross we now know as "the cross" was a later artistic convention, not an archaeological finding.</p>
      <p class="cod-body">But that is only the first problem. The deeper problem is where the two-beamed cross actually came from as a religious symbol. Long before the Messiah, the same shape was already sacred to the worship of <strong>Tammuz</strong>. The letter T — in Hebrew the letter <em>tav</em>, and in Greek the letter <em>tau</em> — was the initial of Tammuz's name, and the T-cross was his mark. Worshippers of Tammuz wore it, drew it on doors, and carried it into their rites. The shape was so associated with him that Yahuah Himself called out the worship of Tammuz by name — in one of the most stunning passages of the entire Old Testament.</p>
      <blockquote class="cod-scripture">
        <p class="cod-scripture-text">Then He brought me to the door of the gate of the house of Yahuah which was toward the north; and, behold, there sat women weeping for Tammuz. Then said He unto me, Hast thou seen this, O son of man? Turn thee yet again, and thou shalt see greater abominations than these.</p>
        <p class="cod-scripture-ref">— Ezekiel 8:14–15</p>
      </blockquote>
      <p class="cod-body">Weeping for Tammuz. A pagan dying-and-rising fertility god whose worshippers wore his T-mark as their sign. Yahuah called it an abomination. And the mark is now displayed in almost every building that claims His name.</p>
      <p class="cod-body">This does not mean the death of the Messiah did not happen. It absolutely did. <strong>It means the object you have been taught to revere is not an accurate depiction of the event — it is an imported pagan shape that was laid over top of the event</strong> as Christianity moved into the Gentile world. The early believers did not wear crosses. The earliest Christian symbols — carved into the catacombs of Rome in the first two centuries — were the fish, the shepherd, the dove, and the anchor. The cross does not appear as a common Christian symbol until the fourth century, when Constantine put it on his army's shields — and Constantine, as the Canon chapter showed, was a worshipper of the sun.</p>

      <section class="cod-part"><p class="cod-part-label">Part Two</p><h2 class="cod-part-title">The Fish</h2><div class="cod-part-rule"></div></section>

      <div class="cod-symbol-intro">
        <div class="cod-symbol-glyph">&#9856;</div>
        <p class="cod-symbol-name">the ichthys — and what it really pointed to</p>
      </div>

      <p class="cod-body">The early believers did use a fish as a symbol. The Greek word for fish, <em>ichthys</em>, was used as an acronym: Iesous Christos Theou Huios Soter — "Jesus Christ, Son of God, Saviour." That part of the story is true, and it is often repeated. What is not often repeated is that the fish symbol was not invented by believers. It was already a sacred mark in the ancient world long before the acronym was invented, and the body of water that produced the fish — the sea — was already a domain associated with a very specific pagan god.</p>
      <p class="cod-body">The Philistines worshipped <strong>Dagon</strong> — a fish-god whose temple Samson pulled down (Judges 16:23–30) and whose idol fell on its face before the Ark of the Covenant (1 Samuel 5:3–4). Dagon imagery is unmistakable. The god was depicted as a man from the waist up and a fish from the waist down. His priests wore a fish-head mitre — a tall pointed hat shaped like an open fish's mouth, with the head of the priest emerging from the fish's body.</p>
      <p class="cod-body">Look at the mitre of the Roman Catholic Pope. The tall pointed hat. The shape shaped like an open fish's mouth. The ceremonial headgear of the head of the largest Christian body on earth is, shape for shape, the mitre of the priests of Dagon. <strong>Coincidence does not survive the visual comparison.</strong> The costume of the fish-priest was inherited wholesale by the institution that produced the canon, the creeds, and the entire visual language most Christians now accept as "Christian."</p>
      <p class="cod-body">This is not to say every believer who puts a fish sticker on his car is worshipping Dagon. Most have no idea. But it is to say that when the system that absorbed the old religion also absorbed its imagery, and then handed that imagery down as "Christian," the unbroken line from Dagon's temple to the modern parking lot is worth noticing. The Messiah compared His followers to fishermen — not to fish. The ones who follow Him are the ones doing the catching. The fish in the ancient water was the worship of another god entirely.</p>

      <details class="cod-deepdive">
        <summary>
          <span class="cod-deepdive-label">
            <span class="cod-deepdive-icon">✦</span>
            <span>
              <span class="cod-deepdive-title">Go Deeper — The Words You Use</span>
              <span class="cod-deepdive-hint">Church, Amen, Hallelujah, Holy — what they actually come from</span>
            </span>
          </span>
          <span class="cod-deepdive-chevron">▾</span>
        </summary>
        <div class="cod-deepdive-body">

          <h3 class="cod-subsection">Church</h3>
          <p class="cod-body">The word the New Testament uses is <em>ekklesia</em> — a called-out assembly. When Tyndale first put the New Testament into English, he translated it <em>congregation</em>. King James's translators were instructed to replace that with <em>church</em>. The English word <em>church</em> descends from <em>kyriakon</em> — "belonging to the lord" — a word that functioned in the Greco-Roman world long before it attached itself to Christian use. Every time you say "I'm going to church," you are using a word the apostles did not.</p>

          <h3 class="cod-subsection">Amen</h3>
          <p class="cod-body">This one is widely debated, and it deserves honest handling rather than a quick conclusion. The Hebrew word <em>amen</em> (אָמֵן) comes from the root <em>aman</em> — meaning firm, faithful, established. It is used throughout the Old Testament and is a legitimate Hebrew word with a legitimate Hebrew meaning. <strong>That said</strong>, an argument has circulated in Hebrew-roots circles that <em>amen</em> derives from <em>Amun-Ra</em>, the Egyptian sun god whose worship Yisra'el would have encountered during the four hundred years in Egypt. The two sound similar in English. The linguistic evidence, however, is that they are not related — the Hebrew word has its own clear root and semantic field. Use the word <em>amen</em> with confidence, but know the debate exists so you can answer it when a brother raises it.</p>

          <h3 class="cod-subsection">Hallelujah</h3>
          <p class="cod-body">This one is a gift. <em>Hallelujah</em> is a direct Hebrew compound — <em>hallel</em> (praise) plus <em>Yah</em> (the short form of the covenant name). "Praise Yah." It is one of the few places in English liturgy where the name of the Father is still spoken aloud. Every time a congregation says <em>hallelujah</em>, they are — whether they know it or not — calling on the name the translators erased nearly seven thousand times elsewhere in their Bibles. Keep the word. Say it often. It is one of the handful of places where the fingerprint of the translator did not reach.</p>

          <h3 class="cod-subsection">Holy, Saint, Sanctify</h3>
          <p class="cod-body">The Hebrew word underneath all three English words is <em>qadash</em> — set apart, separate, consecrated. The English tradition gave us three different-sounding words for a single Hebrew concept — which has obscured a central truth: <strong>to be holy, to be a saint, and to be sanctified are all the same thing</strong>. You were not sanctified into a nicer version of yourself. You were set apart. Called out. Cut off from the world system and joined to a covenant people. That is what the Hebrew actually says, and what the English has spread over three words.</p>

        </div>
      </details>

      <section class="cod-part"><p class="cod-part-label">Part Three</p><h2 class="cod-part-title">Dice, Candles, and Circles of Light</h2><div class="cod-part-rule"></div></section>

      <h3 class="cod-subsection">Dice and the Casting of Lots</h3>
      <p class="cod-body">Modern Christianity barely thinks about dice at all — except on board-game night. In the ancient world, however, dice were not a toy. They were an instrument of <strong>divination</strong>. The Greek term for dice-based divination was <em>astragalomancy</em> or <em>cleromancy</em> — the practice of throwing bones, stones, or marked cubes to discern the will of the gods. Every major Greco-Roman temple had them. They were standard equipment for priests who claimed to interpret omens.</p>
      <p class="cod-body">Yahuah's position on this practice is unambiguous:</p>
      <blockquote class="cod-scripture">
        <p class="cod-scripture-text">There shall not be found among you anyone that maketh his son or his daughter to pass through the fire, or that useth divination, or an observer of times, or an enchanter, or a witch... For all that do these things are an abomination unto Yahuah.</p>
        <p class="cod-scripture-ref">— Deuteronomy 18:10–12</p>
      </blockquote>
      <p class="cod-body">Divination — the use of objects to read supernatural signs — is listed alongside witchcraft and child sacrifice as an abomination. The Roman soldiers at the crucifixion cast lots for the Messiah's garments (Matthew 27:35) — an act of pagan divination performed <em>on</em> His clothing while He hung on the stake. The lots fulfilled prophecy (Psalm 22:18), but they also testified to the spiritual climate of the men who rolled them. <strong>They were divining under the shadow of the one they had just killed.</strong></p>

      <h3 class="cod-subsection">Candles and the Mithraic Fire</h3>
      <p class="cod-body">Every Catholic mass burns candles. Every Orthodox liturgy burns candles. Most evangelical "traditional" services keep them somewhere near the altar. Votive candles — paid for, lit, and left burning for the petition of a saint or the repose of a soul — are everywhere in traditional Christianity. None of them come from the apostles.</p>
      <p class="cod-body">Candle-lighting as a religious act was central to the worship of <strong>Mithras</strong>, the Persian sun-deity whose cult swept through the Roman empire in the centuries around the life of the Messiah. Mithraic initiates lit flames in underground temples as part of their devotion to the sun's power. When Constantine merged Christianity with the Mithraic cult in the fourth century, the candles came with them. The mechanism is still the same: the worshipper pays a coin, lights a flame, and sends his petition upward with the smoke. Scripture never instructs this. The only fire Yahuah ever authorized in worship was the fire on the altar of the Temple — and when Aharon's sons tried to offer "strange fire" that had not been commanded (Leviticus 10:1–2), Yahuah struck them dead on the spot.</p>

      <h3 class="cod-subsection">Halos and Circles of Light</h3>
      <p class="cod-body">Look at any Catholic or Orthodox religious painting. Behind the head of the Messiah, of Mary, of every canonized saint, there is a golden disk — a halo. Believers assume this was a visual shorthand invented by Christian artists to indicate holiness. It was not. The halo is the <strong>solar disk</strong>, the symbol of sun worship that predates Christianity by millennia. It appears behind the heads of Ra in Egyptian art, behind Apollo in Greek art, behind Sol Invictus in Roman coins minted by Constantine. When Christianity absorbed the sun cult under imperial Rome, the solar disk was absorbed with it — placed behind the heads of Christian figures to signal the same thing it had always signaled: that the person depicted belonged to the realm of the sun. It is not a crown of righteousness. It is a sun-ray halo with a new label.</p>

      <div class="cod-divider">◆</div>

      <section class="cod-part"><p class="cod-part-label">Part Four</p><h2 class="cod-part-title">Dawn &amp; Dusk: The Greatest Abomination</h2><div class="cod-part-rule"></div></section>
      <p class="cod-body">In that same vision of Ezekiel 8 — the one that exposed the women weeping for Tammuz — the prophet is shown one more thing. And Yahuah calls <em>this</em> one the greatest of them all.</p>
      <blockquote class="cod-scripture">
        <p class="cod-scripture-text">And He brought me into the inner court of the house of Yahuah, and, behold, at the door of the temple of Yahuah, between the porch and the altar, were about five and twenty men, with their backs toward the temple of Yahuah, and their faces toward the east; and they worshipped the sun toward the east.</p>
        <p class="cod-scripture-ref">— Ezekiel 8:16</p>
      </blockquote>
      <p class="cod-body">Twenty-five men. Standing at the entrance of the Temple. Backs turned on the house of Yahuah. Faces pointed east, toward the rising sun. Bowing. And Yahuah's response, in the very next verse:</p>
      <blockquote class="cod-scripture">
        <p class="cod-scripture-text">Is it a light thing to the house of Judah that they commit the abominations which they commit here? ...therefore will I also deal in fury: Mine eye shall not spare, neither will I have pity.</p>
        <p class="cod-scripture-ref">— Ezekiel 8:17–18</p>
      </blockquote>
      <p class="cod-body">Now picture <strong>Easter sunrise service</strong>. A congregation gathers before dawn. They face east. They bow their heads. They pray as the sun rises over the horizon. They go home feeling they have honored the Messiah's resurrection.</p>
      <p class="cod-body">Scripture called that exact posture — facing east, bowing to the rising sun — the greatest of the abominations committed in Yahuah's house. The Messiah did not rise at dawn. Scripture repeatedly says He was already risen by the time the women reached the tomb "while it was yet dark" (John 20:1). The resurrection did not happen at sunrise. <strong>The sunrise service is not honoring a resurrection. It is a pagan dawn rite that Ezekiel already labeled and Yahuah already condemned.</strong> It has been absorbed into the Christian calendar under the cover of an event that did not actually occur at dawn.</p>
      <p class="cod-body">Add to this that "Easter" itself is the Anglicized form of <em>Ishtar</em> (Eostre, Astarte, Ashtoreth) — the Babylonian fertility goddess whose rites involved eggs, rabbits, and sunrise worship — and the picture completes itself. The translators who inserted "Easter" into Acts 12:4, the believers who gather at dawn on her festival, and the prophet Ezekiel shown this exact scene in the eighth chapter of his book are all looking at the same thing. One of them recognizes it. The other two do not.</p>

      <details class="cod-deepdive">
        <summary>
          <span class="cod-deepdive-label">
            <span class="cod-deepdive-icon">✦</span>
            <span>
              <span class="cod-deepdive-title">Go Deeper — The Rest of the Symbols</span>
              <span class="cod-deepdive-hint">Trinity knot, IHS monogram, steeples, obelisks, domes</span>
            </span>
          </span>
          <span class="cod-deepdive-chevron">▾</span>
        </summary>
        <div class="cod-deepdive-body">

          <h3 class="cod-subsection">The Triquetra (Trinity Knot)</h3>
          <p class="cod-body">The three-interlocking-loops symbol used to represent the Trinity in contemporary Christian design is not a Christian symbol. It is a <strong>Celtic pagan knot</strong> — one of the oldest continuous symbols in European pre-Christian religion, associated with the triple goddess (maiden, mother, crone) and with triadic pagan deities across the Celtic and Germanic worlds. It was grafted into Christian iconography during the conversion of Ireland and the British Isles, when pagan Celts accepted Christianity on the condition that their existing symbols could be retained. The triquetra is one of those retained symbols. The doctrine it now represents is not found in Scripture in the form it is taught — and the symbol it uses to represent that doctrine came from the same Celtic religion the missionaries were supposedly replacing.</p>

          <h3 class="cod-subsection">The IHS Monogram</h3>
          <p class="cod-body">Altar fronts, communion bread wafers, Jesuit seals, and countless Catholic and Protestant artifacts feature the three-letter monogram IHS. The official explanation is that it is an abbreviation of <em>Iesous</em> — the Greek form of the Messiah's name. That explanation is partially true and historically second. The same three letters were used in the Roman world as the monogram of the Egyptian trinity <strong>Isis, Horus, and Seb</strong>. When the Roman church absorbed Egyptian religious imagery under the Isis-fronted Marian cult, the old monogram was retained and given a new official meaning. The letters that now appear on millions of communion wafers carry the stamp of a pagan Egyptian trinity — rebranded but never replaced.</p>

          <h3 class="cod-subsection">Steeples, Obelisks, and Domes</h3>
          <p class="cod-body">The tall pointed tower rising from a Christian building is a <strong>steeple</strong> — and its older cousin, the <strong>obelisk</strong>, is one of the most recognizable symbols of Egyptian sun worship. Obelisks stood in Egyptian temples as phallic-solar shafts dedicated to Ra. Rome transported dozens of them from Egypt and placed them in front of its temples and eventually its churches — the Vatican courtyard centers on a stolen Egyptian obelisk. The church steeple is the Protestant inheritance of that same shape, minus the Egyptian hieroglyphs. The <strong>dome</strong> — the rounded, feminine counterpart — is the architectural form of the womb of the sky-goddess. Every church that displays both a dome and a steeple is displaying the male and female principles of sun-goddess worship in architectural form, usually without knowing it.</p>

          <h3 class="cod-subsection">The Pattern</h3>
          <p class="cod-body">Notice what is happening. Every one of these symbols has a real pagan origin. Every one of them was absorbed by the Roman imperial church as it expanded through Europe. Every one was re-labeled. And every one was handed down as "Christian" to successive generations who had no way of knowing where it came from. <strong>The fingerprints of the absorption are everywhere if you know to look for them.</strong></p>

        </div>
      </details>

      <section class="cod-part"><p class="cod-part-label">Part Five</p><h2 class="cod-part-title">The Principle Behind the Pattern</h2><div class="cod-part-rule"></div></section>
      <p class="cod-body">By now the objection is writing itself in the careful reader's mind. <em>Does Yahuah really care what shape hangs in my sanctuary? If my heart is right, does a symbol matter?</em> That is a question Scripture has answered directly. The answer is yes — and the reason is spelled out in the second commandment:</p>
      <blockquote class="cod-scripture">
        <p class="cod-scripture-text">Thou shalt not make unto thee any graven image, or any likeness of any thing that is in heaven above, or that is in the earth beneath, or that is in the water under the earth: thou shalt not bow down thyself to them, nor serve them.</p>
        <p class="cod-scripture-ref">— Exodus 20:4–5</p>
      </blockquote>
      <p class="cod-body">The commandment is not primarily about craftsmanship. It is about <strong>what you hold up in worship</strong>. Yahuah does not accept being approached through images — His own name, at the burning bush, was <em>I will be what I will be</em>, a refusal to be reduced to an object. When a believer carries a cross, lights a candle, wears a fish, or gathers at sunrise, he is doing what the pagan religions around ancient Yisra'el did — he is approaching the Almighty through a physical object. The commandment stands whether the label on the object says "Tammuz" or "Jesus." <strong>The object is the problem</strong>. The label is cosmetic.</p>
      <p class="cod-body">There is a deeper principle underneath the commandment. The adversary has been offering the same counterfeit in different wrappers for six thousand years. Every generation gets its version. Every culture gets its adaptation. The details change; the structure does not. The structure is always the same: an object, a posture, a rite, and a label — imported from somewhere, handed to you with authority, and accepted without examination. Yahuah's response has also never changed. <strong>Come out.</strong> Not adapt. Not reform. Come out.</p>
      <blockquote class="cod-scripture">
        <p class="cod-scripture-text">Wherefore come out from among them, and be ye separate, saith Yahuah, and touch not the unclean thing; and I will receive you.</p>
        <p class="cod-scripture-ref">— 2 Corinthians 6:17</p>
      </blockquote>
      <p class="cod-body">The separation is not of spirit only. It is of objects. It is of language. It is of posture. It is of calendar. It is of everything the old system handled — including the things it handed you wrapped in religious paper.</p>

      <div class="cod-divider">◆</div>

      <section class="cod-part"><p class="cod-part-label">Part Six</p><h2 class="cod-part-title">The Verdict</h2><div class="cod-part-rule"></div></section>
      <p class="cod-pullquote">Christian or demonic?</p>
      <p class="cod-body">The cross is the mark of Tammuz the translators laid over the death of the Messiah. The fish was Dagon's — and Dagon's mitre still sits on the head of the largest Christian office on earth. Candles are Mithraic. Halos are solar disks. Steeples are Egyptian obelisks. The Triquetra is a Celtic pagan knot. The IHS monogram was Isis, Horus, and Seb before it was Iesous. The sunrise service is the dawn worship Ezekiel called the greatest abomination. Easter is Ishtar. Christmas is Saturnalia. And the Bible says to come out.</p>
      <p class="cod-body">This is not a call to tear the crosses off the walls of every building. It is a call to <strong>see them for what they are</strong>. The believer who knows the origin of a symbol has already broken its power over him. The believer who does not know — who calls these things Christian because he has never been told otherwise — is still inside the system that handed them to him. The first step out is knowledge. The second step is refusal to keep carrying the objects the system used to sell itself to you.</p>
      <p class="cod-body">Yahuah is a jealous Elohim, the same command says — not because He is insecure, but because He will not share the worship that belongs to Him with the objects of any other religion, no matter what label someone has written over the top of them. Worship Him in spirit and in truth. That is what the Messiah said — and spirit and truth leave no room for an imported stake shaped like Tammuz's tau, or a fish-god's hat, or a sunrise rite Ezekiel already condemned.</p>
      <p class="cod-pullquote">Do you know what you're worshipping? Now you do. The question is whether you will keep.</p>

      <div class="cod-end"><span class="cod-end-mark">◆</span></div>
    </div>
